In article <1994May3100.58.51.3885@silverton.berkeley.edu> djb@silverton.berkeley.edu (D. J. Bernstein) writes:
>> On the other hand, allow it to encrypt an A to an A might allow
>> portions of the message to "seep through".
>
>No. You don't give away any information: the cryptanalyst has no way to
>know which portions of the ciphertext happen to match the plaintext.

I agree with this, provided that it is isolated to a single letter, or
even a letter pair.  IMO if words were to seep through then things could
be different.  The chance of that happening, of course depends on the
method being used.

>On the other hand, if you _disallow_ ciphertext letters matching 
>plaintext letters, then you _do_ give away information.
>---Dan

This of course is true.

